value.value: The regionalization process in which information that determines the correct position at which plant organ primordia are formed is generated and perceived resulting in correct positioning of the new plant organ.
The process that determines the orientation of a plant organ or tissue with reference to an axis.

label.value: specification of plant organ axis polarity

value.value: The process in which the polarity of a plant organ axis is specified.

label.value: regulation of timing of plant organ formation

value.value: Any process that modulates the rate, frequency or extent of plant organ formation at a consistent predetermined time point during development.
Catalysis of the reaction: (R)-5-phosphomevalonate + ATP = ADP + CO2 + isopentenyl phosphate + phosphate.
Catalysis of the reaction: FMN + H2O = phosphate + riboflavin.

label.value: basal pole of outer hair cell

value.value: The end of the outer hair cell which receives and transmits neural signals.
Any process of the immune system that can contribute to the formation of immunological memory or an immune response based upon activation of immunological memory.

An immune response mediated by the innate immune system and directed against a previously encountered immunologic stimulus, being quicker and quantitatively better compared with the initial response to that stimulus.
Any immunological memory process that can contribute to the formation of immunological memory.
An immune response directed against a previously encountered antigen, being quicker and quantitatively better compared with the primary response.

label.value: adaptive immune memory response involving T cells and B cells

value.value: An immune response mediated by reactivated memory T cells and B cells and directed against a previously encountered antigen, being quicker and quantitatively better compared with the primary response.
An adaptive immune response that involves one or more immune effector processes and takes place during the effector phase of the adaptive immune response.

label.value: adaptive immune effector response involving T cells and B lineage cells

value.value: An adaptive immune effector response involving T cells and B lineage cells. In the case of B lineage cells, the effector cells are the antibody secreting plasma cells whereas for T cells the effector cells may be helper T cells or cytotoxic T cells.
An adaptive immune response against an antigen not previously encountered by immune system.

label.value: primary adaptive immune response involving T cells and B cells

value.value: An adaptive immune response mediated by naive T or B cells against an antigen not previously encountered by immune system.

The aggregation, arrangement and bonding together of two or more different receptor complexes that individually undergo combination with a hormone, neurotransmitter, drug or intracellular messenger to form a higher level receptor complex. The formation of the higher level complex initiates a change in cell function.
The center of the migrating motile tip of a growing nerve cell axon or dendrite.
The non-central region or periphery of the migrating motile tip of a growing nerve cell axon or dendrite.

A region of the cell cortex that contains a higher concentration of growth polarity factors than the surrounding cortex and that changes position over time. An example is found in fission yeast cells during early mating, in which the GTPase Cdc42 dynamically to discrete zones within the cortex prior to shmoo formation.
Any process that increases brood size. Brood size is the number of progeny that survive embryogenesis and are cared for at one time.
Any process that decreases brood size. Brood size is the number of progeny that survive embryogenesis and are cared for at one time.

Interacting selectively with one or more biological molecules in another (target) organism, initiating pathogenesis (leading to an abnormal, generally detrimental state) in the target organism. The activity should refer to an evolved function of the active gene product, i.e. one that was selected for. Examples include the activity of botulinum toxin, and snake venom.

A four subunit complex, that comprises all the necessary RNA processing enzymes (endonuclease, polynucleotide kinase, and exonuclease) to mediate 'cistronic rRNA transcript ITS2 (internal transcribed spacer) cleavage' (GO:0000448).

label.value: cellular response to very-low-density lipoprotein particle stimulus

value.value: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a very-low-density lipoprotein particle stimulus.
A cellular structure consisting of parallel, hexagonally arranged actin tubules, comprising filamentous actin and disulfide cross-linked cofilin multimers.

A extracellular matrix complex involved in cell adhesion and cell migration. Typically homotrimeric or homohexameric. In mammals, four complexes exist: Tenascin-C, Tenascin-N (also known as Tenascin-W), Tenascin-X and Tenascin-R.

definition.value: An example is Tenascin-N (Q9UQP3) in PMID:17909022 (IDA).

value.value: A region of a chromosome at which DNA damage has occurred. DNA damage signaling and repair proteins accumulate at the lesion to respond to the damage and repair the DNA to form a continuous DNA helix.
The aggregation, arrangement and bonding together of a set of components to form a DNA repair complex.
Binding to a meprin and TRAF homology (MATH) domain.

A process that contributes to the maintenance of proper telomeric length and structure via the activation of telomere shortening pathways that compensate telomerase-dependent excessive telomere elongation. Telomere attrition is mediated by a mechanism which involves the generation of single-stranded C-rich telomeric DNA, and the formation and removal of double-stranded telomeric circular DNA (T-circles). Telomere trimming is an independent pathway to recombination-mediated telomere elongation and the well-documented gradual telomere attrition that accompanies cellular replication.
Any membrane that is part of a pigment granule.

label.value: glycolysis from storage polysaccharide through glucose-1-phosphate

value.value: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of a storage polysaccharide into pyruvate through a glucose-1-phosphate intermediate, with the concomitant production of a small amount of ATP and the reduction of NAD to NADH.

Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a nematicide stimulus. Nematicides are chemicals used to kill nematodes.
The series of molecular signals generated as a consequence of an acetylcholine receptor binding to one of its physiological ligands.
Binding to a ceramide, a class of lipids composed of sphingosine linked to a fatty acid. Ceramides are a major component of cell membranes.
The portion of the mitochondrial inner membrane that is not invaginated to form cristae. The inner boundary membrane lies parallel to the outer membrane.

Combining with an adipokinetic hormone to initiate a change in cell activity. Adipokinetic hormones (AKHs) are protein or peptide hormones that are important for sugar and fat homeostasis in metazoa. In insects, they mobilize sugar and lipids from the insect fat body during energy-requiring activities such as flight and locomotion. They also contribute to hemolymph sugar homeostasis.

Binding to an adipokinetic hormone. Adipokinetic hormones (AKHs) are peptide hormones that are involved in the mobilization of sugar and lipids from the insect fat body during energy-requiring activities such as flight and locomotion. They also contribute to hemolymph sugar homeostasis.

Binding to an adipokinetic hormone receptor. Adipokinetic hormones (AKHs) are peptide hormones that are involved in the mobilization of sugar and lipids from the insect fat body during energy-requiring activities such as flight and locomotion. They also contribute to hemolymph sugar homeostasis.

label.value: regulation of plasma lipoprotein particle levels

value.value: Any process involved in the maintenance of internal levels of plasma lipoprotein particles within an organism.

Catalysis of the reaction: (EE)-geranyllinalool + NADPH + O2 = 4,8,12-trimethyl-1,3,7,11-tridecatetraene + NADP+ + 2 H2O. It is unknown whether this reaction proceeds by the direct release of the 4-carbon compound but-1-en-3-one, or whether the substrate is first degraded to C18-farnesylacetone and then cleaved to produce 4,8,12-trimethyl-1,3,7,11-tridecatetraene (TMTT) and acetone.

Catalysis of the reaction: (E)-nerolidol + NADPH + O2 = (3E)-4,8-dimethylnona-1,3,7-triene + NADP+ + 2 H2O. It is unknown whether this reaction proceeds by the direct release of the 4-carbon compound but-1-en-3-one, or whether the substrate is first degraded to C11-geranylacetone and then cleaved to produce (3E)-4,8-dimethylnona-1,3,7-triene (DMNT) and acetone.
Any process involved in the balance between food intake (energy input) and energy expenditure.

label.value: eukaryotic translation initiation factor 4F complex assembly

value.value: The aggregation, arrangement and bonding together of a set of components to form the eukaryotic translation initiation factor 4F complex.

label.value: cellular response to granulocyte macrophage colony-stimulating factor stimulus

value.value: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a granulocyte macrophage colony-stimulating factor stimulus.

label.value: response to granulocyte macrophage colony-stimulating factor

value.value: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a granulocyte macrophage colony-stimulating factor stimulus.
The volume enclosed by the membrane of a phagocytic vesicle.
All of the contents of a cilium, excluding the plasma membrane surrounding the cilium.

definition.value: Note that we deem cilium and microtubule-based flagellum to be equivalent. Also, researchers consider the composition of both the plasm and the membrane of the cilium to be detectably different from that in the non-ciliary cytosol and plasma membrane (e.g. in terms of calcium ion concentration, membrane lipid composition, and more). For this reason, the term "ciliary plasm" is not linked to "cytoplasm".

value.value: Binding to a L27 domain of a protein. L27 is composed of conserved negatively charged amino acids and a conserved aromatic amino acid. L27 domains can assemble proteins involved in signaling and establishment and maintenance of cell polarity into complexes by interacting in a heterodimeric manner.
